Stash :::
- You are working
- Suddenly need to switch branch
- But work is incomplete
30) git stash             <- Saves changes temporarily (like a locker)
To get it back: git stash pop


What is .gitignore? It is a file where you tell Git:  “Don’t track these files”
- Avoid uploading unnecessary files
- Avoid sensitive data (passwords, API keys)
- Keep repo clean
Example:
node_modules/
.env
*.log

If file is already tracked → .gitignore won’t work
31) git rm -r --cached node_modules



Can we go back to previous commit? YES 
Option 1: Temporary (checkout)
32) git checkout commit_id           <- Just viewing old version (detached HEAD)

Option 2: Permanent reset
33) git reset --hard commit_id         <- Completely go back (delete changes after that commit 

Go to 10th previous commit
34) git reset --hard HEAD~10
Meaning:
- HEAD = current commit
- ~10 = go 10 commits back



Revert all changes, What does "revert" mean?
Undo changes WITHOUT deleting history
35) Command: git revert commit_id
Creates a new commit that cancels previous one

Difference 
Command	                     What it does
git reset	                   Deletes history
git revert	                 Keeps history, adds undo commit



Undo all local changes
36) If not committed:  git restore .
37) Remove staged changes: git reset


38) Delete everything:   git reset --hard


Branch → different path →                                git checkout -b branch
Commit → save point →                                    git add . && git commit -m "msg"
Stash → temporary save →                                 git stash / git stash pop
Tag → version label →                                    git tag v1.0
Reset → go back in time (delete future) →                git reset --hard HEAD~1
Revert → cancel changes safely →                         git revert HEAD
.gitignore → ignore files →                              create .gitignore & add file names



